{{nihongo|'''Ōsasahara Shrine'''|大笹原神社| Ōsasahara Jinja}}) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|en|Shinto shrine|WD=Q845945|lt=Shinto shrine|1=Shinto shrine}} located in the city of {{ill|Yasu, Shiga|en|Yasu, Shiga|WD=Q611642|lt=Yasu|1=Yasu, Shiga}}, {{ill|Shiga Prefecture|en|Shiga Prefecture|WD=Q131358|lt=Shiga Prefecture|1=Shiga Prefecture}}, {{ill|Japan|en|Japan|WD=Q17|lt=Japan|1=Japan}}. The ''[[kami]]'' worshipped at this shrine are [[Susanoo-no-Mikoto]] and [[Kushinadahime]].

==Outline==
Ōsasahara Shrine was constructed in the year 986 by Echi Morozane, a local warlord. In 1414, the shrine's main hall (''[[honden]]'') was reconstructed by Mabuchi Sadanobu, the castellan of Iwakura Castle. Following the [[Meiji Restoration|Meiji restoration]] and the establishment of the [[Modern system of Ranked Shinto shrines]] under {{ill|State Shinto|en|State Shinto|WD=Q1197248|lt=State Shinto|1=State Shinto}}, the shrine was officially designated a “county shrine”. 

==Cultural properties==
;Honden: Reconstructed in 1414 during the middle {{ill|Muromachi period|en|Muromachi period|WD=Q334845|lt=Muromachi period|1=Muromachi period}}, this building is a 3×3 {{ill|Ken (unit)|en|Ken (unit)|WD=Q3195007|lt=''ken''|1=Ken (unit)}}, single-storied structure with an  {{ill|East Asian hip-and-gable roof|en|East Asian hip-and-gable roof|WD=Q855025|lt=''irimoya-zukuri''|1=East Asian hip-and-gable roof}} style {{#tag:ref|(''{{ill|East Asian hip-and-gable roof|en|East Asian hip-and-gable roof|WD=Q855025|lt=East Asian hip-and-gable roof|1=East Asian hip-and-gable roof}}'', 入母屋造): a hip-and-gable roof combining a ridge and two gable {{ill|Pediment|en|Pediment|WD=Q190996|lt=Pediment|1=Pediment}}s on the upper part with a {{ill|Hip roof|en|Hip roof|WD=Q162034|lt=hipped roof|1=Hip roof}} on all sides in the lower part of the roof.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.aisf.or.jp/~jaanus/deta/i/irimoyazukuri.htm |title = ''irimoya-zukuri''| publisher = [[JAANUS|JAANUS – Japanese Architecture and Art Net User System]]| accessdate = 2009-11-08}}</ref>|group="ex"|name="irimoya-zukuri-expl"}} roof and a 1 ''ken'' step canopy covered by [[Chamaecyparis obtusa|hinoki cypress]]  bark shingles.  It is particularly notable for the excellent construction technique of the transom and doors. The ornamental carvings are representative of {{ill|Higashiyama culture|en|Higashiyama culture|WD=Q1036294|lt=Higashiyama culture|1=Higashiyama culture}}.<ref name="shiga-city">{{cite web |url         = http://www.city.yasu.lg.jp/school/shinohara/1464154206656.html |title       = 大笹原神社 |trans-title=Ōsasahara Shrine |publisher   = {{ill|Yasu, Shiga|en|Yasu, Shiga|WD=Q611642|lt=Yasu city|1=Yasu, Shiga}} |accessdate  = April 11, 2020 }}</ref>  <ref name="shiga-pref">{{cite web |url         = http://www.pref.shiga.jp/hodo/e-shinbun/ma07/files/20090713_2.pdf |title       = 大笹原神社本殿 |trans-title=Ōsasahara Shrine main hall |publisher   = {{ill|Shiga Prefecture|en|Shiga Prefecture|WD=Q131358|lt=Shiga Prefecture|1=Shiga Prefecture}} |accessdate  = November 1, 2009 |url-status     = dead |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20110613090900/http://www.pref.shiga.jp/hodo/e-shinbun/ma07/files/20090713_2.pdf |archive-date = June 13, 2011 }}</ref> The building was designated as {{ill|National Treasure (Japan)|en|National Treasure (Japan)|WD=Q1139795|lt=National Treasure|1=National Treasure (Japan)}} in 1961. <ref name="Bunka1">{{cite web |url=https://bunka.nii.ac.jp/db/heritages/detail/189283|title=大笹原神社本殿 |trans-title= Ōsasahara Shrine honden |language=Japanese |publisher=[[Agency for Cultural Affairs]] |accessdate=August 20, 2021}}</ref> 

;Shinohara Shrine Honden: Located to the left of the main shrine is a subsidiary shrine dedicated to [[Ishikori-dome no Mikoto]].  Built in 1425, it was designated an {{ill|Important Cultural Property (Japan)|en|Important Cultural Property (Japan)|WD=Q1188622|lt=Important Cultural Property|1=Important Cultural Property (Japan)}} in 1931.<ref name="Bunka2">{{cite web |url=https://kunishitei.bunka.go.jp/heritage/detail/102/1445|title=大笹原神社境内社篠原神社本殿 |trans-title= Osasahara Shrine Precincts Shinohara Shrine Main Hall |language=Japanese |publisher=[[Agency for Cultural Affairs]] |accessdate=August 20, 2021}}</ref>  

